"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-team-usa-gymnastics-takes-on-cardboard-beds-paris-games\", \"text\": \"Check out Sports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, our daily Olympics podcast from Mitch Goldich and Dan Gartland. Subscribe wherever you get your podcasts (Apple,Spotify) and find clips onSI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s YouTube page.  Now that the U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gymnastics team has made it through Thursday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s podium training\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the practice event at which, three years ago,Simone Biles first began to show signs of the vertigothat would derail her Tokyo Olympics\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094they will all sleep easier.\\u00c2  Not just becauseBiles culminated the session with a breathtaking Yurchenko double pike vault, which suggests that the \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ctwisties,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d as the condition is known, is behind her. There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s also a more elementary reason.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re getting mattress toppers today,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says coach C\\u00c3\\u00a9cile Landi. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHallelujah!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The 13 athletes (five women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s artistic gymnasts, five men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s artistic gymnasts, two trampoline athletes and one rhythmic gymnast) arrived at the Olympic Village north of Paris on Monday. It took about 15 seconds for them to notice a problem: The mattresses felt like rocks.\\u00c2  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI sat on it and I was like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Oh my God,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Landi with a laugh. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was like, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098Mary [McDaniel, who runs logistics]! Help!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Help was already on the way. A few days earlier, the team had announced a partnership with BedJet, which makes a cooling system that attaches to the bed and also offers mattress toppers and sheets that wick away sweat, but the technological problems that swept the world last week delayed the items\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 arrival. The entire delegation expects to receive them Thursday.\\u00c2  Coach Jess Graba lights up at the possibility. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAre we getting any?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he asks. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m pretty sure the athletes will get those. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not sure I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m getting those. If I get one, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be excited.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The U.S. gymnastics team is just the latest squad to identify concerns about the accommodation at the Olympics, although many athletes admit it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been better than what they feared when they first learned of France\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s attempt to keep the enterprise as eco-friendly as possible by building beds from recycled cardboard and eschewing air conditioning. (Team USA immediately purchased portable air conditioning units and brought them to Paris.)\\u00c2  The U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s water polo team recently received mattress toppers as well and the Australian women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s water polo team ordered their own mattress toppers, too.\\u00c2  Many athletes have taken to social media to give tours of the furniture, with British diver Tom Daley bouncing on one bed and Irish rugby players Jordan Conroy and Harry McNulty flinging themselves onto another. So far, the cardboard seems to have held up.\\u00c2  And the athletes are thrilled to have a real village experience, after a Tokyo Olympics marred by isolation. The U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gymnastics team stayed in a hotel in an attempt to mitigate the risks; this time around, they are enjoying even such details as the option to grab a snack. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThey were sliding it under the door for us [in Tokyo],\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Graba recalls.\\u00c2  Landi is a bit less effusive: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe food is what it is,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Landi, who was born in Paris and grew up in Marseille. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not the French cuisine I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m used to, but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not that bad.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d But she concedes that she too is enjoying the village, having already been starstruck by encounters with Spanish tennis player Rafael Nadal and American swimmer Katie Ledecky.  Indeed, everyone seems more relaxed than they did three years ago. The U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gymnastics team declined to speak to the media but left the arena smiling and joking with one another. It will face its first test Sunday, in the qualifying round of the team event. But first: a Friday rest day. Literally.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Stephanie Apstein is a senior writer covering baseball and Olympic sports for Sports Illustrated, where she started as an intern in 2011 and has since covered a dozen World Series and three Olympics. She has twice won top honors from the Associated Press Sports Editors, and her work has been included in the Best American Sports Writing book series. She graduated from Trinity College with a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in French and Italian, and has a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Columbia University.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"